\begin{abstract}
Recent work has theoretically shown that Advantage Actor-Critic (A2C) is a special case of Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) when PPO is constrained to a single update epoch. Building on this insight, we conduct a progressive ablation study to empirically investigate how PPO's learned parameters and behavior converge toward A2C as key mechanisms are systematically removed. We train five model variants (A2C and four PPO configurations) across three random seeds on the CartPole-v1 environment, measuring both task performance and structural similarity via parameter distance metrics. Our results confirm the theoretical prediction: PPO with single-epoch updates (PPO-1) achieves the closest structural similarity to A2C (maximum parameter difference of 0.51 versus 1.81 for default PPO). However, this structural convergence comes with a 6\% performance reduction and increased variance. Most critically, we find that removing PPO's clipping mechanism causes catastrophic training failure (60\% performance drop), demonstrating that clipping is essential for stability even when other mechanisms are A2C-like. Our work provides empirical validation of the PPO-A2C relationship and reveals the performance-stability trade-offs inherent in A2C's constrained design.

\end{abstract}

