\section{Introduction}
Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) \citep{schulman2017ppo} and Advantage Actor-Critic (A2C) \citep{mnih2016a3c} are among the most widely adopted deep reinforcement learning algorithms for game AI and robotics applications. Conventionally, these algorithms have been viewed as distinct methods with different objectives and training paradigms: A2C directly applies policy gradient updates using advantage estimates, while PPO employs a clipped surrogate objective with multiple optimization epochs per batch of experience.

However, recent theoretical analysis by Huang et al.~\citep{huang2022a2c} has challenged this conventional understanding, demonstrating that A2C is mathematically equivalent to PPO when PPO is configured with a single update epoch ($K=1$). Under this configuration, the ratio $\pi_\theta(a_t|s_t)/\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(a_t|s_t) = 1$ during the first update, causing PPO's clipping mechanism to have no effect and collapsing PPO's objective to match A2C's gradient exactly.

While this theoretical equivalence is elegant, it raises important empirical questions: \textit{How does PPO's learned behavior and parameter space evolve as we progressively remove its distinctive mechanisms and approach A2C's configuration?} Does structural convergence in parameter space correspond to convergence in performance and stability? Which of PPO's mechanisms are most critical for its empirical success?

\subsection{Contributions}

In this work, we conduct a systematic empirical study to answer these questions through progressive ablation. The contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
\item We design and execute a controlled ablation study with four PPO variants that progressively approach A2C by removing: (1) multi-epoch updates, (2) Generalized Advantage Estimation (GAE) and advantage normalization, and (3) the clipping mechanism.

\item We introduce a parameter distance metric to quantify structural similarity between learned policies, demonstrating that single-epoch PPO (PPO-1) achieves 3.5× closer parameter alignment with A2C compared to default PPO.

\item Through multi-seed experiments with learning curve analysis, we reveal that structural convergence toward A2C is accompanied by performance degradation and increased training variance, with the removal of clipping causing catastrophic failure (60\% performance drop).

\item We validate the theoretical PPO-A2C equivalence empirically while highlighting the practical importance of PPO's additional mechanisms for achieving stable, high-performance learning.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Related Work}

\subsection{A2C and PPO Algorithms}

Advantage Actor-Critic (A2C) \citep{mnih2016a3c} is the synchronous variant of the Asynchronous Advantage Actor-Critic (A3C) algorithm. A2C maximizes the policy objective:
\begin{equation}
L^{\text{A2C}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_t\left[\log \pi_\theta(a_t | s_t) \hat{A}_t\right]
\end{equation}
where $\hat{A}_t$ is an estimate of the advantage function, typically computed by subtracting the value function from returns.

Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) \citep{schulman2017ppo} introduced a clipped surrogate objective to prevent destructively large policy updates:
\begin{equation}
L^{\text{PPO}}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_t\left[\min\left(r_t(\theta)\hat{A}_t, \text{clip}(r_t(\theta), 1-\epsilon, 1+\epsilon)\hat{A}_t\right)\right]
\end{equation}
where $r_t(\theta) = \pi_\theta(a_t|s_t)/\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(a_t|s_t)$ is the probability ratio. PPO additionally employs multiple update epochs per batch of experience and typically uses Generalized Advantage Estimation (GAE).

\subsection{Theoretical Equivalence}

Huang et al.~\citep{huang2022a2c} proved that when PPO uses a single update epoch ($K=1$), its gradient becomes identical to A2C's gradient. Specifically, during the first epoch, $\pi_\theta = \pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}$, so $r_t(\theta) = 1$ and the clipping operation has no effect. Applying the log-derivative trick shows that $\nabla_\theta L^{\text{PPO}, K=1}(\theta) = \nabla_\theta L^{\text{A2C}}(\theta)$. They validated this empirically by showing that appropriately configured PPO and A2C produce identical trained models in CartPole.

Our work extends this binary equivalence result by studying the \textit{gradient path} from PPO to A2C through progressive ablation, revealing how different mechanisms contribute to the divergence between the two algorithms.

\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Progressive Ablation Design}

We design a four-step ablation ladder that progressively transforms PPO toward A2C:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{PPO-0 (Baseline):} Default PPO with all standard mechanisms enabled (10 epochs, GAE with $\lambda=0.95$, advantage normalization, $\epsilon=0.2$ clipping)

\item \textbf{PPO-1 (Single Epoch):} Set $K=1$ to match A2C's single-update paradigm. This is the theoretically equivalent configuration identified by Huang et al.~\citep{huang2022a2c}.

\item \textbf{PPO-2 (Disable GAE \& Normalization):} Additionally set $\lambda=1.0$ (disabling GAE, matching A2C's advantage estimation) and disable advantage normalization.

\item \textbf{PPO-3 (Remove Clipping):} Set $\epsilon=0.0$ to completely disable the clipping mechanism, making the objective structurally identical to A2C.
\end{itemize}

We also train a standard A2C baseline for comparison. All models share the same policy architecture (2-layer MLP with 64 hidden units), training timesteps (50,000), and evaluation protocol.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}

We measure two complementary aspects of convergence:

\textbf{Performance Metrics:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Final episodic reward (mean and standard deviation over 20 evaluation episodes)
\item Learning curves: reward progression evaluated every 2,000 steps
\item Across-seed variance to assess training stability
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Structural Similarity Metric:}
To quantify parameter-space convergence toward A2C, we compute:
\begin{equation}
d(\text{model}, \text{A2C}) = \max_{\theta_i} |\theta_i^{\text{model}} - \theta_i^{\text{A2C}}|
\end{equation}
where $\theta_i$ ranges over all policy network parameters. This measures the maximum absolute difference in any parameter, providing a conservative estimate of structural similarity.

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

\textbf{Environment:} CartPole-v1, a standard benchmark for policy gradient methods with a maximum episode reward of 500.

\textbf{Training:} We train each configuration for 50,000 timesteps across three random seeds (0, 42, 123). All models use the same MLP policy architecture and are evaluated every 2,000 steps using 10 deterministic rollouts.

\textbf{Implementation:} We use Stable-Baselines3 \citep{raffin2021stable}, a well-tested reinforcement learning library, ensuring implementation correctness. All hyperparameters except the ablated mechanisms are kept constant across configurations (learning rate: 7e-4, batch size: 128 for PPO-0, 5 for others to match A2C).

\textbf{Reproducibility:} We set random seeds for NumPy, PyTorch, and environment initialization. Complete code and hyperparameter configurations are provided in the supplementary materials.

