\textbf{Key Observations:}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{PPO-0 achieves perfect performance:} Default PPO consistently solves CartPole (500 reward) with zero variance across all seeds, demonstrating robust learning.

\item \textbf{Single-epoch updates reduce performance:} PPO-1 shows a 6\% performance drop (471 vs 500) and increased variance ($\pm$33), indicating that multi-epoch optimization contributes meaningfully to PPO's sample efficiency.

\item \textbf{GAE and normalization have limited impact:} Surprisingly, PPO-2 nearly matches PPO-0 performance (494 vs 500), suggesting these mechanisms are less critical than multi-epoch updates for this task.

\item \textbf{Clipping is essential:} Removing clipping (PPO-3) causes catastrophic failure, achieving only 201 mean reward with massive variance ($\pm$132). This represents a 60\% performance drop from PPO-0 and 43\% drop from A2C.

\item \textbf{A2C shows high variance:} A2C achieves moderate performance (353) but with extremely high variance ($\pm$145), with individual seed results ranging from 152 to 487.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Learning Dynamics}

Figure~\ref{fig:learning_curves} reveals critical differences in learning behavior:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{PPO-0 and PPO-2} show smooth, monotonic improvement, reaching optimal performance by 20,000 steps and maintaining stability.

\item \textbf{PPO-1} exhibits slower, more erratic learning with continued fluctuations even after 30,000 steps, never fully stabilizing.

\item \textbf{A2C} shows highly unstable learning, oscillating between 200-500 throughout training without convergence.

\item \textbf{PPO-3} displays catastrophic instability, with multiple complete failures where performance drops near zero (e.g., at steps 20,000 and 40,000 for certain seeds), demonstrating training collapse.
\end{itemize}

