\section{Discussion}

Our results provide strong empirical support for the theoretical equivalence between single-epoch PPO and A2C \citep{huang2022a2c}. PPO-1 achieves the closest parameter-space convergence to A2C, confirming that $K=1$ is the dominant factor in structural similarity. However, this equivalence is \textit{asymmetric}: single-epoch PPO still outperforms A2C (471 vs 353), suggesting implementation details beyond the core objective continue to differentiate the algorithms.

Perhaps our most striking finding is the catastrophic failure of PPO-3 when clipping is removed (201 reward, $\pm$132 variance). This demonstrates that clipping is \textit{essential} for training stability, even when other mechanisms suggest A2C-like behavior should be achievable. Without clipping, small errors in value estimation compound through policy gradient updates, leading to divergence.

The 6\% performance gap between PPO-0 and PPO-1 demonstrates that multi-epoch updates provide meaningful sample efficiency gains, aligning with PPO's original motivation \citep{schulman2017ppo}. Our multi-seed experiments reveal A2C's fundamental instability (performance ranges from 152 to 487), which may explain why PPO has largely superseded A2C in practice.

Our study focuses on CartPole-v1 to enable careful multi-seed analysis. Future work should extend this ablation to more complex environments and alternative metrics.
\section{Conclusion}

This work provides a comprehensive empirical validation and extension of the theoretical result that A2C is a special case of PPO when $K=1$ \citep{huang2022a2c}. Through progressive ablation, we demonstrate that:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Single-epoch PPO (PPO-1) achieves 3.5× closer structural similarity to A2C in parameter space compared to default PPO, confirming the theoretical equivalence.

\item Despite structural convergence, PPO-1 still outperforms A2C by 33\% (471 vs 353 mean reward), revealing that parameter-space similarity does not guarantee equivalent behavior.

\item PPO's clipping mechanism is essential for training stability—removing it causes a 60\% performance drop with catastrophic training failures, even when other mechanisms suggest A2C-like behavior should be achievable.

\item Multi-epoch updates provide meaningful sample efficiency gains (6\% performance improvement), while GAE and advantage normalization have limited impact on CartPole.

\item A2C exhibits high training variance ($\pm$145) that PPO's mechanisms successfully mitigate, explaining PPO's practical dominance despite theoretical equivalence.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Track 1 Contribution:} We have successfully reproduced and extended the core finding of Huang et al.~\citep{huang2022a2c} that A2C is a special case of PPO, providing empirical validation through progressive ablation rather than binary comparison. Our multi-seed experiments with learning curve analysis and parameter distance metrics offer deeper insights into \textit{how} and \textit{why} these algorithms diverge in practice despite theoretical equivalence, contributing practical understanding to the game AI and reinforcement learning communities.

